					<description><![CDATA[<p>Learn how to write compelling calls to action that jump off the page and get more clicks.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">How to Write a Killer Call to Action: 8 Tips &#038; Ideas</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Read to the end of this blog post to receive $1 million!</p>
<p>Oh, if only that were true. However, now that you‚Äôre thinking about the proper way to motivate someone, let‚Äôs talk about the mighty call to action (CTA).</p>
<p>A CTA is the most important element in most marketing messages. Whether you want people to place an order, set an appointment, or subscribe to your email, CTAs are the final step in making it happen.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-duedil.jpg" alt="call to action - example CTA from Duedil" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-76599 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-duedil.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-duedil-480x308.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Look at that blue call-to-action button telling us what to do next.</em></p>
<p>But how do you write a good call to action?</p>
<p>In this guide, we‚Äôll show you how to craft the type of CTAs that jump off the screen and get people to do the one thing you really want them to do. Maybe you won‚Äôt get a million dollars directly, but with your new CTAs at the ready, you‚Äôll generate a lot more business. And that‚Äôs almost as good.</p>
<h3>Table of contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-a-call-to-action">What is a call to action in marketing?</a></li>
<li><a href="#benefits-of-a-call-to-action">The benefits of a good call to action</a></li>
<li><a href="#how-to-write-a-call-to-action">How to write a good call to action</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-a-call-to-action"></div>
<h2>What is a call to action in marketing?</h2>
<p>In marketing, a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/03/07/call-to-action-marketing">call to action</a>, or CTA, is a word or phrase that tells your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/09/18/beginners-guide-to-target-markets">target audience</a> what to do next. They can be plain copy, but they‚Äôre often clickable links either in text or in a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/02/20/call-to-action-buttons">CTA button</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-barkbright.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a landing page from brand Bark Bright" width="923" height="348" class="aligncenter wp-image-76600 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-barkbright.jpg 923w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-barkbright-480x181.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 923px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You can use CTAs in just about any type of marketing message. In fact, a customer might see several CTAs as they move from unaware prospect to repeat buyer.</p>
<p>For example, someone might click a ‚Äúlearn more‚Äù button on your Facebook ad, then click a ‚Äúsubscribe now‚Äù button on your landing page, then click a ‚Äúbuy now‚Äù CTA button from your newsletter.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6a8.png" alt="üö®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Boring CTAs won‚Äôt cut it. Download this free guide of <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download">the 36 best call-to-action phrases ever</a> and start using conversion-boosting CTAs.</p>
<div id="benefits-of-a-call-to-action"></div>
<h2>Benefits of a good call to action</h2>
<p>A call to action is a signpost that leads people down the road of becoming a customer. It helps to keep prospects moving toward that goal so they don‚Äôt veer off and get distracted.</p>
<p>These examples show the influence of a great call to action:</p>
<ul>
<li>Emails with a single CTA increased clicks by <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/06/10/digital-marketing-stats">371%</a> and sales by 1617%.</li>
<li>CTAs on a landing page increased clicks by <a href="https://www.bnpengage.com/blog/call-action-cta-benefits/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">80%</a>.</li>
<li>Adding well-placed CTAs increased revenue from blog posts by <a href="https://www.brafton.com/blog/content-marketing/where-to-place-ctas-for-an-83-increase-in-blog-revenue/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">83%</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Let‚Äôs look at how to create these types of irresistible CTAs.</p>
<div id="how-to-write-a-call-to-action"></div>
<h2>How do you write a good call to action?</h2>
<p>A <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-pros-write-calls-to-action">good call to action</a> will attract attention and make it hard to resist taking the next step in ads, emails, landing pages, and more. Read on to learn how to write CTAs that drive conversions no matter where they are (see what we did there?).</p>
<h3>1. Use a strong verb to start your CTA</h3>
<p>You don‚Äôt have a ton of space to get your point across. Don‚Äôt dilly or dally. Let your audience know exactly what you want them to do by leading each <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/02/20/call-to-action-buttons">CTA button</a> with an action verb.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a call to action page promoting free gift" width="936" height="571" class="aligncenter wp-image-76601 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin-480x293.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>There are different action verbs depending on the type of business you run and what you want your customer to do. Here are a few ideas:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>For an ecommerce website:</strong> Start your CTA with words like ‚Äúbuy,‚Äù ‚Äúshop,‚Äù or ‚Äúorder‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>If you‚Äôre promoting a newsletter or piece of content:</strong> Start your CTA with words like ‚Äúdownload‚Äù or ‚Äúsubscribe‚Äù</li>
<li><b>For a service-based business:</b> Try CTAs that begin with ‚Äúcall now‚Äù or ‚Äúbook your appointment.‚Äù</li>
</ul>
<p>What you don‚Äôt want is to simply say something exists. ‚ÄúOur newest fashions are available‚Äù won‚Äôt stir people to action, whereas ‚Äúclick here for the latest trends‚Äù feels kinetic and is more likely to improve your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/click-through-rate">click-through rate</a>.</p>
<h3>2. Include words that provoke emotion or enthusiasm</h3>
<p>If you want more clicks and conversions, you need to elicit a strong response from your audience. An enthusiastic CTA that taps into <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/05/03/emotional-marketing-copy">emotional copywriting</a> is just the thing to get it done.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a landing page from brand Done Done" width="817" height="583" class="aligncenter wp-image-76602 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone.jpg 817w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone-480x343.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 817px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs say someone is looking to book a trip with their family. They come across a CTA like ‚Äúplan your dream vacation today!‚Äù That‚Äôll get them hyped and thinking about what their dream vacation looks like. They‚Äôll eagerly click the link in your ad.</p>
<p>Some other ways your CTAs can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/01/13/best-words-and-phrases-for-marketing">tap into emotion include</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Reducing risk and insecurity</li>
<li>Building trust</li>
<li>Creating urgency</li>
<li>Communication value</li>
</ul>
<p>Don‚Äôt forget punctuation. Add an exclamation point to the end of your CTA to max out the excitement. It‚Äôll make your CTA pop and give it a little extra kick.</p>
<h3>3. Give your audience a reason to act</h3>
<p>In other words, tell people what‚Äôs in it for them if they click. Will it help them do their jobs better, lose weight, or save money? This will tie in heavily with your value proposition, or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/04/07/unique-selling-proposition">unique selling point</a> (USP). Your USP is arguably one of the most important pieces of acquiring new leads, so creating a nice USP/CTA mash-up is a great way to increase clicks.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of landing page with CTA from brand slider" width="842" height="589" class="aligncenter wp-image-76603 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider.jpg 842w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider-480x336.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 842px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>A good <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/13/call-to-action-examples">example of a call to action</a> here would be something like ‚Äúcall us to start saving money today!‚Äù Not only have you stated the action you want the user to take (call today), but you have also provided them with a reason why they should take that action (save money).</p>
<h3>4. Take advantage of FOMO</h3>
<p>This is actually one of my favorite tactics when it comes to a successful CTA. Fear of missing out, otherwise known as <a href="http://psychcentral.com/blog/archives/2011/04/14/fomo-addiction-the-fear-of-missing-out/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FOMO</a>, is an extremely effective motivator. When people think they might lose out on an opportunity that might not come around again, they‚Äôll be mighty quick to hop on the bandwagon.</p>
<p>One of the best uses of FOMO in your CTA is to mention a sale or promotion that your company is holding, and which won‚Äôt last forever.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1.jpg" alt="call to action - Screenshot of an ad with CTA for shop now" width="370" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-76604 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1.jpg 370w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1-185x300.jpg 185w" sizes="(max-width: 370px) 100vw, 370px" /></p>
<p>You probably get emails with this sort of messaging all the time, I know I sure do. I‚Äôm talking about messaging like ‚ÄúShop today! Sale ends on Monday,‚Äù perhaps during a three-day weekend. Or even ‚Äúbuy now while supplies last!‚Äù during the holiday season. It‚Äôs tough to ignore a prompt like that, especially during a time-sensitive, under-the-gun type of situation (e.g. the Christmas season).</p>
<p>Similar to provoking enthusiasm as we discussed earlier, provoking fear of missing out in your CTA is sure to get you some additional clicks.</p>
<h3>5. Match CTA to device type</h3>
<p>Creating a killer call-to-action is important, that‚Äôs no secret. But I also urge you to consider customizing your CTA based on the device being used by your audience. Google considers <a href="http://searchengineland.com/the-real-reason-why-google-is-dropping-the-tablet-vs-desktop-distinction-its-the-user-context-stupid-149738" target="_blank" rel="noopener">desktop and tablet as the same device</a>, since the screen sizes are roughly the same. People also use them for search in similar scenarios.</p>
<p>For example, someone sitting on the couch at night sees an ad on TV for a product they‚Äôre interested in. It‚Äôs common for them to grab their laptop or tablet and search for more information on it. It might be best to lead them with a ‚Äúlearn more‚Äù or ‚Äúshop now‚Äù CTA.</p>
<p>However, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/08/18/mobile-ad-strategies">mobile devices tend to have different user behavior</a> and search intent than desktop/tablets. Since <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/local-seo-statistics/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">80%</a> of searches for local business on mobile devices convert, it‚Äôs prudent to tailor your CTA based on device..</p>
<p>One big difference between desktop and mobile is that on mobile, people have the ability to place a call from the device they‚Äôre shopping with. My advice is to create more phone call-centric CTAs that appear on mobile devices, especially for service-based businesses. This lawn care company has a clickable phone number on their landing page.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a landscapers website with clickable phone number" width="356" height="595" class="aligncenter wp-image-76605 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape.jpg 356w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape-179x300.jpg 179w" sizes="(max-width: 356px) 100vw, 356px" /></p>
<p>Some possible <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/powerful-call-to-action-phrases/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CTA phrases</a> to try could be ‚Äúcall now to get started‚Äù or ‚Äúcall us today for more information‚Äù to guide your target audience to take the action you want them to take.</p>
<h3>6. A/B test your CTAs</h3>
<p>A good, old-fashioned <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2012/09/25/a-b-testing">A/B test</a> is a great way to identify which CTA‚Äôs bring you clicks, and which CTA‚Äôs bring you frowns. While your tried and true <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/20/call-to-action-examples">calls-to-action</a> like the ones we‚Äôve already discussed are always good to use, you really never know how they‚Äôll perform in your account until you actually use them.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt.jpg" alt="call to action - Comparision of two ads from Dewalt" width="926" height="384" class="aligncenter wp-image-76606 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt.jpg 926w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt-480x199.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 926px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Digital marketing is definitely a game of trial and error (which is why it can be frustrating!), and your calls-to-action are no exception to the rule. Something could look great on paper, or may sound great when a colleague recommends it to you, but the only way you‚Äôll absolutely know for sure if something will work for your account is if you test it out.</p>
<p>Your target audience may not respond well to what could be considered a ‚Äúsurefire CTA,‚Äù which is enough to make you pull your hair out. By A/B testing, you can trial some <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2010/09/29/unusual-effective-calls-to-action">creative CTAs</a> and compare them to your old standards. If your target audience isn‚Äôt responding well to your ads, you might as well try to think outside the box a bit!</p>
<p>Start with:</p>
<ul>
<li>Check out today‚Äôs deals!</li>
<li>Fill out a form to get started</li>
<li>Call today for more information</li>
</ul>
<p>And test against:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tons of deals at your fingertips</li>
<li>A healthier life starts now!</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt miss out, call us today!</li>
</ul>
<h3>7. Add numbers when possible</h3>
<ol start="7"></ol>
<p>We consumers respond well to seeing numbers such as pricing, discounts, promotions, incentives, etc. It helps us to determine whether or not it‚Äôs worth splurging on items we desperately want, but probably aren‚Äôt essential to everyday life. So when the opportunity arises, why not appeal to your target audience that way?</p>
<p>I am always a big proponent of including pricing information in your ad copy in general, and that includes your CTA. If a user sees your pricing information in your ad, and decides to click through to your site, then you know they are still interested in the product or service you are offering. Now you know you have yourself a valuable click, and an increased chance at generating a conversion.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna.jpg" alt="call to action - landing page from brand Luna with subscribe CTA" width="557" height="584" class="wp-image-76607 size-full aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna.jpg 557w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna-480x503.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 557px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>But, if you don‚Äôt include your pricing information in your ads, someone may click through to your site, excited about your products/services, but then get scared off by your prices. Now you have yourself a less than desirable situation. This leads to the dreaded wasted spend in your account, and who wants to deal with that?</p>
<p>Try experimenting with your pricing information in your CTA, as well as any other applicable numerical information. A CTA such as ‚ÄúShop today for TVs under $300!‚Äù not only shows a user how little they will pay for a TV, but it also hits on the FOMO element as well (pretty sneaky huh?).</p>
<p>If you run a special promotion for shipping, you could try something like ‚Äúorder by Sunday for 1-day shipping.‚Äù Maybe you are an auto body shop looking to incentivize your audience with a discount; your CTA might look something like ‚ÄúBook today! 15% off your next visit.‚Äù</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Want more tips on creating ads that convert? Get your copy of our free <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSContentDLWebBlogInContentTextLinkAllStarPlaybook.html?cid=Web_Blog_InContent_TextLink_AllStarPlaybook_Download">all-star playbook for online advertising</a>.</p>
<h3>8. Be bold in your CTA copy</h3>
<p>This can be a little risqu√©, but adding a dash of brash to your CTA copy can be pretty effective in catching someone‚Äôs eye.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of an ad for a conference with a bold CTA" width="789" height="587" class="aligncenter wp-image-76608 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam.jpg 789w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam-480x357.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 789px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>One option that can be tough to pull off is using negative words to motivate a person to change something they are self-conscious about. For example, if I was on Google looking to lose weight and saw a call-to-action such as ‚Äúend your crappy diet today,‚Äù I might just want to click. Sure, it‚Äôs a bit over-the-top, which is why I recommend using this technique sparingly, but it definitely commands attention.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs another example. Say I want to fix the brown patches in my lawn. I‚Äôm perusing Google and see an ad with a CTA like ‚Äúyour yard sucks, let us fix it.‚Äù Not only would I probably chuckle, but I would also probably click just to see exactly what that lawn company could do for me. You‚Äôre walking a fine line with this technique, but it can pay off.</p>
<h3>Boost conversions with strong calls to action</h3>
<p>Whether it‚Äôs on your website, social media ads, search engine listings, or newsletter, a well-written call to action will get more people to take the next step toward making a purchase.</p>
<p>Remember these eight tips to write a good call to action:</p>
<ol>
<li>Use a strong verb to start your CTA</li>
<li>Include words that provoke emotion or enthusiasm</li>
<li>Give your audience a reason to act</li>
<li>Take advantage of FOMO</li>
<li>Match CTA to device type</li>
<li>A/B test your CTAs</li>
<li>Add numbers when possible</li>
<li>Be bold in your CTA</li>
</ol>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">How to Write a Killer Call to Action: 8 Tips &#038; Ideas</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
